      "text": "Tabular data is organized into a two-dimensional structure of rows and columns, much like an Excel spreadsheet or a Google Sheet. This format is conceptually identical to a two-dimensional array: a series of lists where each element is separated by a specific character.\n\n### Common Formats\n*   **CSV (Comma-Separated Values):** Uses a comma (`,`) as the delimiter between values.\n*   **TSV (Tab-Separated Values):** Uses a tab character to separate values.\n\n### Visualizing the Structure\nWhile we often view data in a clean, formatted table with orange headers and organized rows, the underlying text file is much simpler. \n\nIf you were to open a `.csv` file in a basic text editor, the data for a city list would look like this:\n\n```text\nID,Name,Lat,Long,Pop.\n1,London,-50,0,8000000\n2,New York,-70,-40,8000000\n3,Amsterdam,-50,5,2000000\n```\n\nIn a `.tsv` file, the structure remains the same, but the commas are replaced by tabs:\n\n```text\nID\tName\tLat\tLong\tPop.\n1\tLondon\t-50\t0\t8000000\n2\tNew York\t-70\t-40\t8000000\n3\tAmsterdam\t-50\t5\t2000000\n```\n\n### Accessing Tabular Data in Code\nBecause of this structure, you can access data points using two methods:\n1.  **By Index:** Referencing the specific column number and row number (e.g., `data[row][column]`).\n2.  **By Header:** Using the labels provided in the header row to identify specific columns.",
      "heading": "Tabular Data: CSV and TSV",
